{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01HUyhZeRxqpFpHbB8urQqy2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior for this Python CLI tool that reads a git repository and produces a summary of recent changes.\n\nThe tool:\n- Reads a git repository\n- Produces a summary of recent changes (files added, deleted, renamed, modified)\n- Outputs structured report to stdout\n- Runs in CI pipelines and developer environments\n\nLet me think through each behavior:\n\n**Behavior 1: Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about how the tool parses/categorizes git output. The failure is in the categorization logic itself - could be a parsing bug or logic bug. \n\nThe real question is whether I'm testing the parsing logic in isolation or the actual git behavior. If the parsing function is isolated, this could be a unit test, but I need to understand whether the tool calls git as a subprocess and correctly interprets git's rename detection. Git's rename detection has thresholds and specific output formats like R100, so testing this properly requires a real git repository with an actual rename operation. A mock might not capture git's actual behavior accurately.\n\nI'm leaning toward System level testing because the tool needs to shell out to git and handle its actual output format, though if the implementation uses a library like GitPython instead of shelling out, that could change things.\n\nFor the binary files behavior, I definitely need a real git repo with actual binary files to test whether the tool crashes when encountering git's binary diff markers—mocking the subprocess output might work for parsing, but the real failure mode depends on how git actually formats binary diffs.\n\nThe empty repository case also requires system-level testing: I need to create a real git repo with no commits to see if the tool handles the \"fatal: bad default revision 'HEAD'\" error gracefully or crashes.\n\nFor counting accuracy, I'm verifying against a real repository with known history to ensure the numbers match what actually happened. And for the staged versus unstaged behavior, I need to test both states in a real git repo to confirm the output is identical regardless. I'm realizing that behavior 1 might actually be testable at a lower level if I can mock the git subprocess output with known formats—the core issue is just parsing logic around how renames get categorized versus counted as separate deletions and additions. But to catch real failures reliably, I'd still need to verify against actual git output, which pushes it back to System level.\n\nAll five behaviors ultimately require a real git repository and subprocess to test properly—whether it's detecting renames, handling binary files, dealing with repos that have no HEAD, verifying commit counts, or managing staged changes. Integration-level testing with mocked git output wouldn't give me the confidence I need here.\n\nNow I'm assigning probability distributions across test levels for each behavior. Behavior 1 (rename detection) has a small chance of being caught at Unit with good parsing isolation, but System testing dominates at 70% since I need an actual repo with a real rename. Behavior 2 (binary file crashes) is almost certainly System-level at 80%—I need real binary files in a real repository. Behavior 3 (empty repo edge case) also requires a genuine empty git repo since git's behavior is specific to that state.\n\nFor the remaining behaviors, behavior 4 (commit count accuracy) needs real git history to verify correctness, and behavior 5 (staged vs unstaged distinction) requires an actual staging area with real changes. All three cluster around 80-88% System probability since the tool's core failure modes depend on actual git behavior and repository state that can't be reliably mocked.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9751,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9751},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d5430327-11de-4d56-a7ac-39936ab3deba","uuid":"380b303c-b168-449e-9f85-76d5052eb2fe"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01HUyhZeRxqpFpHbB8urQqy2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Y8mXi9436KVRcvfBfbGSyh","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is in how git rename status (R100 old new) is parsed and routed vs. how deletions (D) and additions (A) are counted. This is a parsing/categorization logic bug. In isolation you could unit-test the parser with a hard-coded git status string. REAL-INFRA: However, git's rename detection is threshold-based and its output format (--name-status R vs. --diff-filter=R) varies by invocation. The exact output the tool receives depends on how it calls git. A real git repo with an actual rename (content similarity ≥ threshold) is needed to expose whether the tool invokes git with flags that suppress or expose rename detection. Mocking the subprocess output presupposes you already know the correct format the tool uses — a circular test. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: in-process mocking hides any flag/invocation bug at the git call site. REJECTION-GATE for Unit: the parsing function receives whatever the tool passes to git; unit-testing the parser alone doesn't verify the correct git command is used.","test_description":"Create a real git repo via subprocess (git init, git add, git commit). Then rename a file (git mv old.txt new.txt, git add, git commit or stage only). Run the CLI tool against this repo and parse its stdout report. Assert the renamed file appears exactly once under the 'renamed' category, with count 0 for additions and deletions attributable to that file.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.7,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Diffs that include binary files do not cause the tool to crash; binary files are counted in the output.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is a crash — likely the tool tries to decode binary diff output as UTF-8 text, or attempts to parse 'Binary files a/foo and b/foo differ' as a normal diff hunk. REAL-INFRA: Git emits a special marker for binary files in its diff output. The exact bytes and format of that marker (including the null-byte detection path git takes) only appear with real binary content in a real repo. Mocking subprocess output with a plausible string doesn't guarantee the mock matches the real format git actually emits for every binary type (images, compiled artifacts, etc.). The crash is triggered by real git output; a mock that happens to look right would always pass. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: an in-process mock of the subprocess could be made to match, but it would be testing the mock rather than the tool's resilience to actual git output.","test_description":"Create a real git repo, commit a binary file (e.g., a small PNG or a file with null bytes written in Python), then modify it and either stage or commit the change. Run the CLI tool as a subprocess against this repo. Assert: exit code is 0 (no crash), the binary file appears in the 'modified' (or appropriate) category in the output, and the count is ≥ 1.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.83,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Running the tool on a repository that has no commits yet produces an empty report rather than an error.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: An empty git repository (git init, no commits) has no HEAD ref. Any git command that references HEAD — git log, git diff HEAD, git status against HEAD — exits with a non-zero status and a fatal error message. The failure mode is the tool either crashing, printing an error, or exiting non-zero when it encounters this. This behavior is entirely a function of real git's response to a HEAD-less repo; it cannot be reproduced with mocked subprocess output without already knowing the exact error string git emits. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: no in-process wiring of modules can reproduce git's 'fatal: bad default revision HEAD' condition — it is a property of the real git process. REJECTION-GATE for Unit: there is no pure-function logic that can be unit-tested here; the failure is in the tool's error-handling around the subprocess call.","test_description":"Create a temporary directory and run git init inside it (no commits). Run the CLI tool as a subprocess pointing at this empty repo. Assert: exit code is 0, stdout is a valid (empty) report (e.g., all category counts are 0 or the report structure is present but empty), and stderr contains no error message.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.89,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The counts in the report match the actual change history of the repository being analyzed.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: This is an end-to-end correctness claim: the numbers the tool reports must match what is actually in the repo. The failure mode is miscounting — off-by-one, double-counting, or missed files — which only becomes visible when the tool's output is compared against ground truth from a known repo state. REAL-INFRA: Constructing that ground truth requires a real git repo with a controlled, known sequence of changes (add N files, delete M files, rename K files, modify J files). The tool must then be run against that repo and its output validated against the known counts. Mocking git's output to return pre-canned counts is circular: you'd be testing that the tool echoes back what you told it, not that it correctly counts real changes. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: module-wiring tests can verify data flows but cannot verify that the counts are correct against a real change set.","test_description":"Create a real git repo and perform a known sequence of operations: add 3 files, delete 1 file, rename 1 file, modify 2 files — all committed (or staged, depending on the tool's scope). Run the CLI tool as a subprocess. Parse the structured stdout report and assert each category count exactly matches the known ground-truth (added=3, deleted=1, renamed=1, modified=2).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.82,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The output is identical whether the changes being analyzed are staged or unstaged.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: Git's staging area (index) is a real OS-managed data structure separate from the working tree. The tool must invoke different git commands or flags to observe staged vs. unstaged changes (git diff --cached vs. git diff). Whether these two code paths produce identical structured output is a question about real git state. You cannot test this with a mock because you'd need to construct two different fake subprocess responses and assert they produce the same output — which again tests the mock rather than the tool. The failure mode is that the tool uses the wrong git invocation for one of the two states (e.g., always reads unstaged changes even when called in staged mode). REJECTION-GATE for Unit: there is no pure logic to test here — it is a property of which git command the tool calls in each mode. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: in-process module wiring does not reproduce git's index/working-tree distinction.","test_description":"Create a real git repo with a known base commit. Make a set of changes to tracked files without staging them (unstaged). Run the CLI tool and capture its stdout report. Then stage exactly the same changes (git add) without committing. Run the CLI tool again and capture its stdout report. Assert the two reports are byte-for-byte identical (same categories, same counts, same file names).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.87,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9751,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9751},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d5430327-11de-4d56-a7ac-39936ab3deba","uuid":"611bbc93-41d1-4838-a77f-0bbbc25928df"}
